[1] Malaysia (Kelantan)
Date: Mon 27 Jun 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Malaysian National News Service [edited]
<http://www.bernama.com.my/bernama/v3/news.php?id=141989>


Floods cited as reason for typhoid outbreak in Kelantan
-----------------------------------------------
The floods in Kelantan at the end of 2004 have been cited as one of
the major causes for the typhoid that hit the state early in 2005,
the State Legislative Assembly was told on Mon 27 Jun 2005. The State
Exco for Local Governments, Housing and Health, Takiyuddin Hassan,
said the floods had resulted in the overflow of sewage, which
polluted water in wells, and the problem was aggravated by the
subsequent drought.

The government had called on the people to use water supplied by Air
Kelantan Sendirian Berhad and to refrain from using well water, he
said, when replying to a supplementary question. He said the state
government had also identified a food handler from a neighboring
country who had been confirmed as being the carrier of the disease.
Laboratory tests showed that the drinks sold by the food handler had
been contaminated with animal and human feces.

Takiyuddin said that, following the typhoid outbreak, the number of
people visiting Kelantan had dropped, but the situation had
normalized in the past 2 months.

He said 698 typhoid cases had been detected since 3 Apr 2005, and
following this, action had been taken to tackle the outbreak with the
cooperation of the Health Department, Kota Baharu Municipal Council,
and other local authorities.

